<p><i>Eighteen months later, the fledging Web network declared bankruptcy, and a small consortium acquired its assets, including <b>Invasion of a Small World</b>. Eager to recoup their investment, the new owners offered all eight episodes as a quick-and-dirty DVD package. When sales proved somewhat better than predicted, a new version was cobbled together, helped along by a genuine ad budget. The strongest initial sales came from the tiny pool of determined fans—young and well educated, with little preference for nationality or gender. But the scientists in several fields, astronomy and paleontology included, were the ones who created a genuine buzz that eventually put <b>Invasion</b> into the public eye.</i></p>

